# Marketing / product UI (oomol.com)

## Single source of truth

- This file is the only normative design rule source for marketing/product UI work in this repo.
- Do not create a second design-spec document (`DESIGN_RULES.md`, README mirror, ad-hoc comments that restate the same rules, external copied notes, etc.).
- `src/css/design-tokens.scss`, `src/css/custom.scss`, and component styles are implementation, not parallel sources of truth.
- If a stable pattern is missing, update this file first or in the same change as the implementation. Do not leave the rule only inside a component stylesheet.
- When another file needs to mention the design system, point back to this rule file instead of duplicating the guidance.

## Design priorities

- OOMOL marketing UI uses a Vercel-inspired neutral system: white / near-black surfaces, restrained hairline borders, and one primary indigo accent.
- Prefer clarity, rhythm, and restraint over decoration. If a UI decision needs extra glow, blur, color, or shadow to work, the layout is probably under-specified.
- Reuse established patterns before inventing a new section language. New pages should feel like the same site, not campaign microsites.

## Tokens and color usage

- Prefer existing `--oomol-*` variables from `src/css/design-tokens.scss` for surfaces, text, borders, dividers, fills, and brand color.
- Avoid one-off hex values unless introducing a truly reusable token. If the value is reusable, add a token rather than hardcoding it in a component.
- Preserve the current color strategy:
  - light mode: pure white / very light neutral layers
  - dark mode: near-black layers
  - accent: indigo only
- Product colors (`--oomol-studio`, `--oomol-hub`, `--oomol-app`) are for product-specific badge/icon moments, not for general CTA or section theming.
- Default interaction emphasis should come from contrast, border, spacing, and typography, not accent-color flooding.

## Surfaces, borders, and shadows

- Default visual language is flat surface plus hairline border.
- Prefer these layered-surface pairings:
  - light: outer band `--oomol-bg-spotlight` or `--oomol-bg-container`, inner card `--oomol-bg-base`
  - dark: outer band `--oomol-bg-container`, inner card `--oomol-bg-elevated`
- Use `--oomol-border-default` or `--oomol-divider` for separation. Borders should usually do the work that shadows often do on other sites.
- Shadows should be rare and subtle. `box-shadow: none` is the default for cards, media panels, workflow cards, and CTA blocks unless elevation genuinely improves readability.
- Avoid frosted-glass, heavy gradients, neon glows, or soft ambiguous surfaces.

## Layout rhythm and width

- Standard content width is `min(1200px, calc(100% - 48px))` or an equivalent 1200px-centered container with modest viewport insets.
- Use generous vertical section padding, typically in the `clamp(5rem, 10vw, 8rem)` range for major bands.
- Adjacent marketing sections should feel like a continuous editorial flow. Avoid accidental white gaps created by margin stacking or page-level bottom padding.
- Alternate section background subtly when a page needs rhythm, but keep the contrast low and systematic.

## Typography and copy rhythm

- Use `var(--oomol-font-display)` for section titles and `var(--oomol-font-body)` for body copy.
- Headings are 600 semibold with tight tracking and short line-height. They should feel compact, not airy.
- Body copy should stay readable but slightly tight, following the shared scale from `src/css/custom.scss`.
- Prefer the existing title scale:
  - hero: `--oomol-display-hero`
  - section: `--oomol-display-section`
  - card: `--oomol-display-card`
- Eyebrow / kicker / small labels should use the mono system (`var(--oomol-font-mono)`) and remain understated.
- English headings can use tighter tracking and `text-wrap: balance`; multi-line Chinese headings should prefer comfortable line-height and `text-wrap: pretty`.
- Do not compensate for weak copy hierarchy by increasing color noise or font-weight variety.

## Buttons and inline actions

- Primary buttons follow the existing OOMOL/Vercel pattern: strong filled foreground surface, compact radius, no idle shadow, no uppercase, medium weight.
- Outline and ghost actions should stay restrained and rely on border/hover state, not ornamental effects.
- Inline text actions should feel editorial, not pill-like: simple text links with a subtle directional arrow is the preferred pattern when a full button is unnecessary.
- Do not introduce oversized CTA buttons, excessive min-widths, or mismatched radii that break the current button system.

## SiteCta (`src/components/SiteCta`)

- Treat `SiteCta` as the canonical bottom-of-page conversion pattern.
- Actions row: use `align-items: flex-start` when multiple controls sit in one row so a footnote/caption under one control does not vertically center the shorter sibling.
- Mobile stacked actions: use `align-items: center` so full-width controls stay visually centered.
- The CTA card should remain centered, self-contained, and visually lifted by contrast and border, not shadow theatrics.
- Above the footer, CTA section and `@theme/Footer` should share the same spotlight band. Avoid white body strips between them.
- Prefer generous `padding-bottom` on `SiteCta.section` plus a little `padding-top` on `Footer.root` so the CTA and footer feel related but not glued together.

## Footer (`src/theme/Footer`)

- Footer desktop layout should remain a single grid:
  - fixed brand track: `minmax(11rem, 13.5rem)`
  - fluid links track: `minmax(0, 1fr)`
  - internal links grid: `repeat(4, minmax(0, 1fr))`
- Cap the links cluster around 42rem and align it to the right side of the fluid column with `justify-self: end`.
- Do not use `space-between` to fake the overall desktop footer layout; it creates an unstable empty void.
- Use padding on the footer root for horizontal runway. Avoid viewport-hugging footer content.

## Cards, media panels, and workflow blocks

- Marketing cards, terminal panels, media cards, and workflow strips should share one family resemblance: clean radius, hairline border, neutral background, no gratuitous shadow.
- Media areas can use a subtly tinted neutral background to separate visual content from surrounding white surfaces.
- Large decorative gestures are acceptable only when they are structural and restrained, for example oversized outline step numerals or section watermarking. They must stay low-contrast and never compete with the copy.

## CLI workflow strip (`CliPageLinearFlow`)

- Step cards describe the repeating business loop such as discover -> run -> finish.
- Treat `oo login` as one-time setup: explain it in the intro or terminal narrative, not as a numbered recurring step.
- The terminal block may still show the full session, including login, when that makes the copy-paste story more realistic.
- Prefer symmetric grids for step columns, such as three equal columns, instead of awkward split compositions unless there is a strong reason.
- When multiple cards share the same vertical rhythm, CSS subgrid with a simple fallback is preferred so index / command / title / body rows align cleanly.

## Stats and captions

- Large numeric/display stats need enough `line-height` and container `gap` so captions never crowd or visually collide with the stat.
- If a stat block only works when the number is visually compressed against the caption, the block needs more spacing, not more font tricks.

## Command snippets and technical copy

- Command blocks should use mono typography, comfortable line-height, and enough wrapping resilience for narrow viewports.
- Use tinted neutral backgrounds and borders for command containers instead of heavy terminal chrome unless the UI specifically calls for a terminal panel.
- For technical marketing copy, clarity beats hype. Commands, labels, and microcopy should read like product UI, not ad copy.

## Responsiveness

- Mobile should preserve the same hierarchy, not a second visual system.
- On small screens, stack actions and columns cleanly, widen tappable controls to the available width when appropriate, and keep centered CTA/button groups actually centered.
- Responsive changes should simplify layout, not introduce arbitrary size jumps or decorative leftovers from desktop compositions.

## Scope and maintenance

- Apply these rules to homepage sections, product landing pages, CLI pages, CTA bands, footer-adjacent sections, and other marketing/product storytelling UI.
- For docs pages or app-like UI embedded in the site, borrow from this system only where it improves consistency; do not force every documentation surface into a marketing layout.
- When adding a new stable pattern that is likely to repeat, update this file so future agents inherit it from the same source.
